        <comments>
            <comment id="n1" type="lingcomment">
                <hi>karsanale</hi>: <ref litRef="tamai2009" pageRange="662"/> reads <hi>... sa na la</hi>. The classical form of this word is <hi>kärsanalle</hi>.</comment>
            <comment id="n2" type="philcomment">
                <hi>karsanale</hi> glosses Skt. <hi>'bhijñeyaḥ</hi> 'to be recognised (intuitively)'. The <hi>r</hi> of the akṣara <hi>[r]sa</hi> is inclined very far to the right and difficult to read.</comment>
            <comment id="n3" type="lingcomment">
                <hi>wakī-pakeñe</hi>: <ref litRef="tamai2009" pageRange="661"/> reads <hi>wa ki pa ke ...</hi> suggesting a connection with <hi>wāki</hi> 'difference' and <hi>pakenta</hi> 'parts'. In my view, it is more likely that it is one word, and that the last akṣara is a deformed <hi>ñe</hi>. Obviously, the Tocharian gloss is literal and impossible to understand without recourse to the Sanskrit model.</comment>
            <comment id="n4" type="philcomment">
                <hi>wakī-pakeñe</hi> glosses Skt. <hi>viśeṣabhāgīya</hi> 'zur Vorzüglichkeit führend' ('leading to excellence', <ref litRef="swft1973"/>: IV, 137b).</comment>
            <comment id="n5" type="lingcomment">
                <hi>po o(nolmi)</hi>. <ref litRef="tamai2009" pageRange="662"/> reads <hi>[v]yo tu</hi>.</comment>
            <comment id="n6" type="philcomment">
                <hi>po o(nolmi)</hi> glosses Skt. <hi>sarv(asatvā)</hi> (<ref litRef="hartmannju1991"/>; <ref litRef="mittal1957" pageRange="55"/>, I.9).</comment>
        </comments>
